This is a solid collaborative project that combines code exploration, teamwork, and documentation—perfect for building your portfolio while demonstrating real-world development practices. Here are SMART goals tailored to your situation and learning objectives:

### Team-Level Goals

**Goal 1: Select and Validate Game by Day 2**
- Specific: Choose an open-source Python Arcade game with accessible code (under 500 lines initially)
- Measurable: Game runs without errors on all team members' machines
- Achievable: Use GitHub search or existing Arcade examples
- Relevant: Ensures smooth exploration phase and reduces debugging delays
- Time-bound: Complete by end of Day 2

**Goal 2: Complete All Code Changes by Day 5**
- Specific: Visual change + gameplay change + refactor/comments all implemented
- Measurable: Each change compiles and runs; changes are observable in gameplay
- Achievable: Assign clear ownership (Developer 1 handles visuals, Developer 2 handles gameplay)
- Relevant: Leaves buffer time for integration and testing
- Time-bound: Finish by end of Day 5

**Goal 3: Deliver Polished README and Documentation by Day 9**
- Specific: README includes what was changed, why, and how to run it; inline comments explain each modification
- Measurable: Minimum 3–5 inline comments per change; README has setup instructions and change summary
- Achievable: Team Lead drafts template, developers add their section details
- Relevant: Demonstrates communication skills and makes changes transparent for grading
- Time-bound: Complete by end of Day 9

### Individual Goals (Adjust Based on Your Role)

**If You're Team Lead:**
- Specific: Set up version control (GitHub), confirm game runs on Day 1, and identify 2–3 code sections for modifications
- Measurable: Repository created with README template; game launches successfully
- Achievable: Use GitHub Desktop or command line (familiar from your coursework)
- Relevant: Builds project management and infrastructure skills
- Time-bound: Complete setup by Day 2

**If You're Developer (Visual or Gameplay):**
- Specific: Make one isolated change (e.g., background color or enemy speed) and document it with 3+ inline comments
- Measurable: Change is visually or functionally observable; code follows PEP 8 style
- Achievable: Start with a small, low-risk modification before expanding
- Relevant: Demonstrates code reading and modification skills
- Time-bound: Finish by end of Day 5

### Presentation Goal

**Goal 4: Deliver Confident 5-Minute Presentation by Dec at 1:30 PM**
- Specific: Practice presentation script 2 times before the date; demo the game live with before-and-after comparisons
- Measurable: Stay within 5-minute limit; hit all three talking points (intro, visual change, gameplay change)
- Achievable: Assign one speaker per role; create a backup laptop with the game ready
- Relevant: Demonstrates communication and technical confidence
- Time-bound: Present on Tues, Dec at 1:30 PM

